# Scaffolder conventions

`ai-toolkit` is a code generator, not an application. The hardest mistakes
come from confusing scaffolder code with the product code it emits.

## The two-axis mental model

| Axis             | Scaffolder code                          | Product code (templates)              |
|------------------|------------------------------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Location         | `src/ai_cli/{main,commands,generators}/` | `src/ai_cli/templates/<name>/`        |
| Runtime          | Runs when user invokes `ai-cli`          | Runs when user runs the generated app |
| Imports visible? | Yes — scaffolder imports them            | No — verbatim text until rendered     |
| Type-checked?    | Yes (`ty check`)                         | No (excluded via `[tool.ty.src]`)     |
| Dependencies     | Scaffolder's `pyproject.toml`            | Template's own `pyproject.toml`       |

When a rule feels ambiguous, re-derive the answer from this table.

## Adding a new CLI command
1. `src/ai_cli/commands/<name>.py` exposing a Click command
2. Import and register in `src/ai_cli/main.py`
3. Extend the `expected` set in `tests/test_cli_structure.py::test_cli_group_has_all_commands`
4. Update `AGENTS.md` invariant #3 — the 9-command list is load-bearing

## Adding a new template
1. Files under `src/ai_cli/templates/<name>/` — product code
2. `src/ai_cli/generators/<name>_generator.py`
3. Register in `src/ai_cli/commands/templates.py` (the `TEMPLATES` dict)
4. Template's dependencies go in the template's own `pyproject.toml`, never in
   the scaffolder's

## Path constants
`PROJECTS_ROOT` and `TEMPLATES_DIR` live in `ai_cli.constants`. Always route
through that module so tests can monkeypatch it — see
`tests/test_cli_structure.py::test_list_handles_missing_directory` for the
pattern (monkeypatch the constant on **both** `ai_cli.constants` and the
importing module).

## Imports
Absolute imports only: `from ai_cli.commands.new import new`, never
`from .new import new`. Enforced by ruff.

## If a `ty` error fires in a template file
This is expected behavior, not a bug. Templates import packages (`openai`,
`langgraph`, etc.) that the scaffolder does not depend on. Add or verify the
path exclusion in `[tool.ty.src].exclude`; do not "fix" the import.

